<BLOCK1><TI>CLAIM</TI>
<P>1. The Plaintiff's claim is for:
<P1>(a) damages for breach of the duty of fairness, breach of the duty to act in good faith, breach of contract and/or breach of fiduciary duty in an amount to be specified;</P1>
<P1>(b) aggravated damages in an amount to be specified</P1>
<P1>(c) punitive damages in an amount to be specified;</P1>
<P1>(d) pre-judgment interest and post-judgment interest pursuant to sections 128 and 129, respectively, of the Courts of Justice Act, R.S.O. 1990, c. C. 43, as amended;</P1>
<P1>(e) the costs of these proceedings on a substantial indemnity basis; and</P1>
<P1>(f) such further and other relief as this Honourable Court may deem just.</P1></P>
<P>2. The Plaintiff, Vivian Bercovici, is an individual currently residing in Tel Aviv, Israel. The Plaintiff is the former Ambassador of Canada to Israel. The Plaintiff held the position of Canada's Ambassador to Israel from on or about February 14, 2014 to June 30, 2016.</P>
<P>3. By Order in Council, the Plaintiff became a public servant effective on or about January 2, 2014 at the invitation of the Government of Canada. The Plaintiff was appointed to the position of Ambassador to Israel for a four-year term with an opportunity to extend the term.</P>
<P>4. On or about April 21, 2016, the Plaintiff was advised that her appointment would be terminated. The Plaintiff eventually learned that the effective date of the termination would be June 30, 2016.</P>
<P>5. During the period April 21 to June 30, 2016, the Plaintiff made substantial efforts to address numerous pressing issues arising from the termination of her appointment. The responsible officials rebuffed and ignored her, advising her that the Government of Canada could do whatever it wanted to her.</P>
<P>6. The Defendant was required to deal with the Plaintiff honourably, fairly, in good faith and not capriciously.</P>
<P>7. When appointing the Plaintiff to the position of Ambassador to Israel and thereafter, the Defendant gave her assurances about her appointment and tenure that reasonably and legitimately led the Plaintiff to expect that her appointment would only be terminated in good faith and according to a fair process. However, the Defendant ultimately terminated her appointment in a harsh and vindictive manner that had the purpose and effect of harming the Plaintiff. The Defendant's conduct was in bad faith, violated the duty of fairness owed to the Plaintiff, and was contrary to the Plaintiff's legitimate expectations.</P>
<P>8. During the Plaintiff's tenure as Ambassador, she served as a public servant according to terms that were contractual in nature. In the course of terminating her appointment, the Defendant engaged in breach of contract.</P>
<P>9. Given the unique nature of the relationship between the Plaintiff and the Government of Canada, the Defendant was under a fiduciary duty to act in the best interests of the Plaintiff, which the Defendant violated through its conduct.</P>
<P>10. As a result, the Defendant is liable to the Plaintiff for the relief set out in paragraph 1 above.</P>
