<BLOCK1><TI>FACTUM OF THE PLAINTIFF</TI>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">PART 1: NATURE OF THE MOTION</TI>
<P>1. This is a motion to amend the style of cause to add the names of five proposed additional Defendants, Katie Telford, Mark Gwozdecky, Daniel Jean, Barbara Richardson, and Alexandra Bugailiskis.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART 2: BACKGROUND</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI>Parties</TI>
<P>2. The Plaintiff, Vivian Bercovici (&ldquo;Ms. Bercovici&rdquo;), is the former Canadian Ambassador to Israel. She was appointed to her position by the Prime Minister, and served at his pleasure. She is 57 (fifty-seven) years of age. She currently resides in the City of Tel Aviv, in the country of Israel. She is an entrepreneur, freelance writer and the sole income earner for her and her daughter, who resides with her.</P>
<P>3. The organizational Defendant, the Attorney General, is a Ministry of the Federal Government, and carries out its functions as a government entity on behalf of the Crown.</P>
<P>4. The proposed individual Defendant, Mr. Gwozdecky, was Director General, Middle East and Maghreb until November 2015, when he was appointed Assistant Deputy Minister International Security and Political Affairs, Ministry of Foreign Affairs.</P>
<P>5. The proposed individual Defendant, Mr. Jean now retired, was at all material times the Deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs and, subsequently as of May 16, 2016 the National Security Advisor to the Prime Minister of Canada.</P>
<P>6. The proposed individual Defendant, Ms. Bugailiskis, is currently the Canadian Ambassador to Italy, San Marino, Albania and High Commissioner to Malta. However, formerly, and at all material times, she was the Assistant Deputy Minister of Europe, the Middle East and Maghreb and the Ministry of Foreign Affairs.</P>
<P>7. The proposed individual Defendant, Ms. Richardson, is the Canadian Ambassador to the Czech Republic. However, formerly, and at all material times, she was the Inspector General for the Ministry of Foreign Affairs.</P>
<P>8. The proposed individual Defendant, Ms. Telford, is currently, and was at all material times, the Chief of Staff to the Prime Minister of Canada, Justin Trudeau.</P>
<P>9. The organizational Defendant and all proposed Defendants are represented by the same counsel, Mr. Barney Brucker of the Ministry of Justice.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART 3: FACTS</TI>
<P>10. This claim arises out of significant abuse and harassment inflicted on the Plaintiff by key individuals in the Public Service within the Department, who actively worked to undermine and question the Plaintiffs competency, loyalty and professionalism.</P>
<P>11. The Plaintiff commenced an action by issuance of a Notice of Action issued on June 29, 2018, prepared by Plaintiff's original counsel.</P>
<P>12. The style of cause in the Notice of Action lists the Attorney General as the sole Defendant.</P>
<P>13. The Notice of Action contains allegations against the Attorney General as well as &ldquo;responsible officials&rdquo;</P>
<P>14. The Plaintiff changed counsel after the filing of the Notice of Action.</P>
<P>15. Counsel for the Plaintiff prepared a Statement of Claim, with a style of cause that included the five additional proposed Defendants, prior to the deadline for filing of the Statement of Claim.</P>
<P>16. The court Registrar refused to accept a Statement of Claim with a style of cause that was not identical to that contained in the Notice of Action;</P>
<P>17. The Plaintiff was, therefore, forced to file a Statement of Claim on July 30, 2018 that although made claims against the proposed additional Defendants in the body of the pleading, did not include their names in the style of cause.</P>
<P>18. The Plaintiff put the proposed Defendants' counsel on notice during a phone call on August 21, 2018 and by way of follow-up email of August 23, 2018, that the Plaintiff intended to seek an amendment to the Statement of Claim to add the proposed additional Defendants to the style of cause.</P>
<P>19. At the Case Conference on November 16, 2018, counsel for the proposed Defendants, advised that the Plaintiff would have to bring a motion and that they would object.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">PART 4: ISSUES AND THE LAW&mdash;RULE 14.03(5)</TI>
<P>The Plaintiff submits that the following issues must be considered on this motion:
<P1>a. Was the refusal by the Court Registrar of the Plaintiff's original Statement of Claim on the grounds that the style of cause in the Notice of Action did not match that in the Statement of Claim proper?</P1></P>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>RULES WITH RESPECT TO COMMENCING A PROCEEDING BY NOTICE OF ACTION</UNDER></TI>
<P>20. The Plaintiff seeks to have the style of cause in the Statement of Claim amended, <EM>nunc pro tunc</EM>, to include the names of the proposed additional Defendants.</P>
<P>21. Rule 14.06(1) requires, &ldquo;every originating process to contain a title of the proceeding setting up the names of all the parties and the in which they are made parties, if other than their personal capacity.&rdquo;
<P1><BOLD>REF: <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure, RRO 1990, Reg 194, r. 14.06 (1)</EM>.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>22. Rule 14.03(2), states that, &ldquo;where there is insufficient time to prepare a statement of claim, an action may be commenced by issuing a Notice of Action (Form 14C) that contains a short statement of the nature of the claim.&rdquo;
<P1><BOLD>REF: <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure, RRO 1990, Reg 194, r. 14.03 (2)</EM>.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>23. Rule 14.03(5), states that for &ldquo;an action commenced by the issuing of a notice of action, the statement of claim may alter or extend the claim stated in the notice of action.&rdquo;
<P1><BOLD>REF: <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure, RRO 1990, Reg 194, r. 14.03 (5)</EM>.</BOLD></P1></P>
<BLOCK4><N>a.</N><TI><UNDER>Was the refusal by the Court Registrar of the Plaintiff's original Statement of Claim, on the grounds that the style of cause in the Notice of Action did not match that in the Statement of Claim proper?</UNDER></TI>
<P>24. The Plaintiff argues that the very intent of section 14.03(2) is to allow a proceeding to be commenced by providing, &ldquo;a short statement of the nature of the claim,&rdquo; where there is be insufficient time to prepare a statement of claim. A Notice of Action is intended to be brief with the expectation that the details of the claims made will be expanded upon, at a later time, in the Statement of Claim.</P>
<P>25. In light of the brevity of a Notice of Action, as contemplated by the <EM>Rules</EM>, the Plaintiff is permitted the opportunity in a Statement of Claim, pursuant to Rule 14.03(5), &ldquo;...to alter or extend the claim stated in the notice of action.&rdquo;
<P1><BOLD>REF: <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure, RRO 1990, Reg 194, r. 14.03 (5)</EM>.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>26. The Plaintiffs Notice of Action contains allegations against the Attorney General and &ldquo;responsible officials.&rdquo; It sets out the nature of the claim as required by Rule 14.03(2).</P>
<P>27. The Statement of Claim initially presented to the Registrar, named &ldquo;the responsible officials&rdquo; contained in the Notice of Action and expanded upon the claims made against them, as permitted under Rule 14.03(5).</P>
<P>28. Furthermore, the Court Registrar provided no basis in the <EM>Rules</EM> upon which refusal of the Plaintiffs original Statement of Claim was grounded.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="V">PART 5: ISSUE AND THE LAW&mdash;TECHNICAL IRREGULARITY</TI>
<P><P1>a. In the event that the Court finds that refusal by the Registrar of the Plaintiffs original statement of claim was warranted based on the <EM>Rules</EM>, the Plaintiff asks the court to consider whether the omission of the names of all the Defendants in the style of cause, where their names and the allegations against them appear in the body of the Statement of Claim, is a technical irregularity based on non-compliance with Rule 14.06(1)?</P1>
<P1>b. Does s. 21(1) <EM>of the Limitations Act</EM> preclude a technical amendment to the style of cause?</P1></P>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>TEST FOR ORDERING AMENDMENT TO CORRECT A TECHNICAL IRREGULARITY</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK4><TI>RULES OF CIVIL PROCEDURE AND LIMITATIONS ACT</TI>
<P>29. Rule 14.06(1) requires, &ldquo;every originating process is to contain a title of the proceeding setting up the names of all the parties and the capacity in which they are made parties, if other than their personal capacity.&rdquo;
<P1><BOLD>REF: <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure, RRO 1990, Reg 194, r. 14.06 (1)</EM>.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>30. Rule 2.01 states that &ldquo;a failure to comply with the rules is an irregularity, and does not render a proceeding or a step, document or order in a proceeding a nullity.&rdquo; Rule 2.01(a), &ldquo;authorizes a court to grant amendments or other relief as necessary to secure the just determination of &ldquo;the real matters in dispute.&rdquo;
<P1><BOLD>Ref: <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure, RRO 1990, Reg 194, r. 2.01(1) and 2.01(a)</EM>.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>31. The Plaintiff also relies on Rule 5.03(1), which states that, &ldquo;every person whose presence is necessary to enable the court to adjudicate effectively and completely on the issues in a proceeding shall be joined as a party to the proceeding.&rdquo;
<P1><BOLD>Ref: <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, RRO 1990, Reg 194, r. 5.03(1)</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>32. The Plaintiff's position is further supported by Rule 5.04(2), which states that, &ldquo;at any stage of a proceeding the court may by order add, delete or substitute a party or correct the name of a party incorrectly named, on such terms as are just, unless prejudice would result that could not be compensated for by costs or an adjournment.&rdquo;
<P1><BOLD>REF: <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure, RRO 1990, Reg 194, r. 5.04(2)</EM>.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI>CASELAW</TI>
<P>33. In <CASEREF><SOC>Hastings v. Halton Condo Corp.</SOC></CASEREF>, counsel for the Plaintiff failed, due to inadvertence, to include the name of a Defendant in the style of cause of the Statement of Claim. The Court ruled that this failure was an irregularity and outlined the factors that led to this conclusion:
<ITEM><P>Material facts supporting the claim against the Defendant have been pled;</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>The proposed party was put on notice and aware that he/she was an intended Defendant;</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>The statement of claim names the proposed Defendant as a party Defendant;</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>The statement of claim assigns blame to the party Defendant and clearly sets out the basis for same;</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>&ldquo;There is a coincidence between the plaintiffs intention to name a party and the intended party's knowledge that it was the intended defendant,&rdquo; and</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>There is a lack of prejudice to the intended Defendant by the proposed amendment to the style of cause.</P></ITEM>
<P1><BOLD>REF:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Hastings v. Halton Condo Corp</SOC><CITE>2013 ONSC 175</CITE><PARANUM>13 and 16</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>34. The Plaintiffs position is also supported by the case of <CASEREF><SOC>Silic v Ottawa</SOC></CASEREF>, in which the Court stated that, &ldquo;the omission from the style of cause in the writ of summons of the name of a second plaintiff, whose name appears in the endorsement of such writ, is a mere irregularity and permission to amend does not have the effect of setting up a new cause of action.&rdquo;
<P1><BOLD>REF:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Silic v. Ottawa Transportation Commission</SOC><CITE>[1963] 2 O.R. 477139</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD><EM>(Headnote)</EM>.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>35. The Plaintiff also relies on the case of <CASEREF><SOC>Dupuis v. W.O. Stinson &amp; Son Ltd.</SOC></CASEREF>, in which the plaintiffs Statement of Claim was rejected by the court Registrar on the final day of the limitation period, because plaintiff's counsel couriered the statement of claim along with the appropriate fee to the courthouse instead of having someone attend personally, as required by the <EM>Rules</EM>.
<P1><BOLD>REF:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Dupuis v. W.O. Stinson &amp; Son Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 4317</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2014 CarswellOnt 10117</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF><BOLD>.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>36. In <EM>Dupuis, the Court</EM> stated that &ldquo;this case does not involve an order to extend the limitation period but rather an order to correct an irregularity; given that the Statement of Claim with the proper style of cause arrived at the courthouse within the limitation period but was rejected by the Registrar.&rdquo;
<P1><BOLD>REF: <EM>Ibid.</EM></BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI>APPLICATION OF THE LIMITATIONS ACT TO PLEADING AMENDMENTS</TI>
<P>37. The application of the <EM>Rules</EM> and caselaw must be considered in the context of section 21(1) of the <EM>Limitations Act</EM>, which states that, &ldquo;If a limitation period in respect of a claim against a person has expired, the claim shall not be pursued by adding the person as a party to any existing proceeding.&rdquo;
<P1><BOLD>REF: <EM>Limitations Act, 2002, c. 24, Sched. B, s. 21(1)</EM>.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>38. Section 21(2) of the <EM>Limitations Act</EM> states that, &ldquo;Subsection (1) does not prevent the correction of a misnaming or misdescription of a party.&rdquo;
<P1><BOLD>REF: <EM>Limitations Act, 2002, c. 24, Sched. B, s. 21(2)</EM>.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>39. In <EM>Hastings</EM>, where counsel for the Plaintiff omitted the name of a Defendant from the style of cause due to inadvertence, and fully pled allegations against the Defendant in the Statement of Claim, the Court acknowledged that the omission of the party defendant from title of proceedings was not a case of misnomer as contemplated by Section 21(2). Notwithstanding, the Court in <EM>Hastings</EM> stated the following at paragraph 14:
<QUOTE><P>In my view, section 21(1) of the <EM>[Limitations] Act</EM> is not designed to prevent a technical amendment of the pleadings in circumstances where the party has been named as a defendant in the statement of claim and the allegations against him are set out with particularity. The case at bar is distinguishable from the case of <CASEREF><SOC>Streamline Foods Ltd. V Jantz Canada Corp.</SOC><CITE>2012 ONCA 174</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. C.A</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, relied on by the respondent...In <EM>Streamline Food Ltd.</EM>, it was also necessary to plead additional material facts to support the corporation's claim. The Court of Appeal found that the appellants were not seeking to correct the name of a party but rather that they were seeking to add a party and pursue that party's claims and that they were prohibited from doing so by the operation of the Act. In the case at bar, material facts supporting the plaintiffs' claim against Mr. Germann are set out in the claim. To permit the amendment to the style of cause is to allow the remediation of a technical irregularity and is not contrary to the purpose of section 21(1) of the <EM>Act</EM> which is to give the defendant certainty and finality. I conclude that the plaintiffs in this case are not seeking to add Mr. Germann as a party contrary to section 21(1) of the <EM>Act</EM> and that the amendment to the style of cause should be permitted.&rdquo;</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>REF:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Hastings v. Halton Condo Corp</SOC><CITE>2013 ONSC 175</CITE><PARANUM>14</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>.</BOLD></P1></P>
<BLOCK5><N>a.</N><TI><UNDER>Is the omission of the names of the Defendants in a style of cause, where their names and the allegations against them appear in the body of the Statement of Claim, a technical irregularity?</UNDER></TI>
<P>40. The Plaintiff submits that the facts surrounding the addition of Katie Telford, Mark Gwozdecky, Daniel Jean, Barbara Richardson, and Alexandra Bugailiskis meets all the factors outlined in <EM>Hastings</EM> above.</P>
<P>41. The Plaintiff argues that it is not seeking an extension of a limitation period but rather a n order to correct an irregularity. The irregularity being non-compliance with Rule 14.06(1), which requires all parties to the action to be named in the title of proceedings.
<P1><BOLD>REF: <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure, RRO 1990, Reg 194, r. 14.06 (1)</EM>.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>42. The Plaintiff presented the Statement of Claim, containing the names of the additional proposed Defendants in the style of cause and allegations against them, to the Court by the required deadline, however, it was rejected by the Registrar.</P>
<P>43. The Plaintiff argues that an amendment to the style of cause to include the names of the proposed Defendants would not result in prejudice that could not be compensated for by costs or an adjournment.</P>
<P>44. From the outset, the Plaintiff's Statement of Claim named the proposed Defendants and outlined the allegations against them.</P>
<P>45. Counsel for the Attorney General, Mr. Brucker, is also counsel for the five proposed additional Defendants.</P>
<P>46. On August 21, 2018, less than one month following service of the Notice of Action and Statement of Claim on July 31, 2018, Mr. Brucker was informed of the Plaintiffs intention to add the proposed individual Defendants. He advised that he expected to be retained by the proposed Defendants.</P>
<P>47. The proposed additional Defendants, therefore, received notice of the claims against them, as of that point and likely earlier.</P>
<P>48. Furthermore, this action is still in its infancy. The Statement of Defence has not been served nor have discoveries taken place.</P></BLOCK5>
<BLOCK5><N>b.</N><TI><UNDER>Does s. 21(1) <EM>of the Limitations Act</EM> preclude a technical amendment to the style of cause?</UNDER></TI>
<P>49. Lastly, the Plaintiff submits that, as found in <EM>Hastings</EM>, section 21(1) of the <EM>Limitations Act</EM> was not intended to prevent technical amendments.</P></BLOCK5></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="VI">PART 5: ORDER REQUESTED</TI>
<P>The Plaintiff seeks the following relief:
<P1>a. an Order amending the style of cause to add Katie Telford, Mark Gwozdecky, Daniel Jean, Barbara Richardson and, Alexandra Bugailiskis as Defendants to the herein action, <EM>nunc pro tunc</EM>;</P1>
<P1>b. The costs of this motion on a substantial indemnity basis; and</P1>
<P1>c. Such further and other relief as counsel may advise and this honourable Court shall permit.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED THIS 10<SUP>th</SUP> day of December, 2018.</BOLD></P>
