<BLOCK1><TI>FACTUM OF THE DEFENDANT (RESPONDING PARTY)</TI>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">PART I: <UNDER>OVERVIEW</UNDER></TI>
<P>1. The Plaintiff moves to amend the Statement of Claim to add five individuals, Katie Telford, Mark Gwozdecky, Daniel Jean, Barbara Richardson, and Alexandra Bugailiskis, as Defendants to this action in order to maintain claims against each of them for monetary damages based on allegations of intentional infliction of mental suffering at various times while the plaintiff served as Canada's Ambassador to Israel during the period January 2, 2014 to June 30, 2016.</P>
<P><BOLD>2.</BOLD> The Plaintiff has been represented by experienced counsel throughout her dealings with the Government of Canada that are the subject of this action. The Notice of Action filed on June 29, 2018 makes no mention of any of the individual defendants, nor does it include a claim for damages for the tort of intentional infliction of mental suffering. The Statement of Claim also makes clear that the Plaintiff was well aware of the identities of the individuals she wishes to add as defendants and their alleged tortious actions as described in the Statement of Claim well before June 30, 2018.</P>
<P>3. Prior to the delivery of the Statement of Claim, neither the proposed individual defendants nor the Attorney General of Canada (AGC) were put on notice regarding the Plaintiff's intention to make a claim against the aforementioned individuals or any individuals.</P>
<P>4. Contrary to her characterization of this motion as a request to correct a technical irregularity or misnomer, the amendment the Plaintiff seeks would allow her to assert claims against the individuals which are statute-barred pursuant to the <EM>Limitations Act, 2002</EM><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>SO 2002, c 24, Sched. B, ss. 4, 5 and 21. The Limitation period applicable to the proposed claims against the individuals sought to be added as defendants expired at the latest on June 30, 2018.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> thus depriving them of substantive rights in addition those claims as alleged in the Statement of Claim disclose no cause of action and are not tenable at law.</P>
<P>5. The Respondent requests that the Plaintiff's motion to amend the Statement of Claim be dismissed with costs.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART II: <UNDER>FACTS</UNDER></TI>
<P>6. On June 29, 2018, the Plaintiff commenced an action solely against the Attorney General of Canada by way of a Notice of Action.</P>
<P>7. In the Notice of Action, the Plaintiff's sole claim is for damages against the AGC for breach of the duty of fairness, breach of the duty to act in good faith, breach of contract and/or breach of fiduciary duty.</P>
<P>8. On July 31, 2018, the AGC was served with a Statement of Claim naming the AGC as the sole Defendant in the style of cause. Within the body of the Claim, the Plaintiff added the names of the five individuals noted above as well as a new claim for the tort of intentional infliction of mental suffering/against these individuals. None of the proposed individual defendants were served with the original Statement of Claim.</P>
<P>9. On August 21, 2018, three weeks following the service and filing of the original Statement of Claim, the Plaintiff's counsel informed counsel for the Respondent during a telephone conversation that she intended to seek an amendment to the Statement of Claim to add the proposed five individual defendants to the style of cause.</P>
<P>10. On August 23, 2018, the Plaintiff's counsel, Ms. Natalie MacDonald, wrote a letter to counsel for the Respondent to follow up on the telephone conversation of August 21. In that letter, Ms. MacDonald notes that she requires his consent to amend the Statement of Claim to add the individual defendants to the style of cause.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Motion Record of the Plaintiff (MRP), Affidavit of Ursula Nicola, at para 10, Exhibit &lsquo;E&rsquo;.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>11. On August 24, 2018, counsel for the Respondent wrote an email to Ms. MacDonald actually sent to her on August 27, 2018 explaining that he was not in a position to consent to the addition of the proposed individual defendants without clarification as to the retainer and being instructed accordingly.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Motion Record of the Respondent (MRR), Affidavit of Camelya Buchanan, at paras 2 and 3, Exhibits &lsquo;A&rsquo;. and &lsquo;B&rsquo;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>12. On October 1, 2018, Ms. MacDonald emailed counsel for the Respondent asking for confirmation of instructions from the proposed individual defendants regarding adding them as defendants in the style of cause.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>MRP, Affidavit of Ursula Nicola, at para 11, Exhibit &lsquo;F&rsquo;.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>13. On October 5, 2018, counsel for the Respondent confirmed that he had been retained by three of the five proposed individual defendants. He explained that the necessary approvals from the appropriate government authorities who must authorize representation have not yet been finalized with respect to two of the proposed defendants, being Daniel Jean and Katie Telford and that instructions would be required from the proposed individual defendants as to their consent to be added as such.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>MRP, Affidavit of Ursula Nicola, at para 12, Exhibit &lsquo;G&rsquo;.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Counsel for the Respondent suggested that the parties proceed to a case conference stating that the case would benefit from case management.</P>
<P>14. On October 16, 2018, counsel for the Respondent among other things again advised Ms. McDonald that instructions would be required from the individuals as to their proposed addition as defendants to the action.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>MRP, Affidavit of Ursula Nicola at para 13, Exhibit &lsquo;H&rsquo;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>15. On November 16, 2018, the parties attended a Case Conference before Justice Sandra Nishikawa. At that time, Counsel for the Respondent advised that he had been retained as counsel on behalf of the proposed individual defendants and that he was instructed to resist the Plaintiff's request to add each of the individuals as defendants to this action.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART III: <UNDER>POINTS IN ISSUE</UNDER></TI>
<P>16. This motion raises the following issues:
<P1>(i) Whether the Plaintiff is entitled to amend the Statement of Claim to add the proposed five individuals as defendants to this action pursuant to the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RRO, Reg. 194.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> and the <EM>Limitations Act, 2002</EM>; and,</P1>
<P1>(ii) Whether the claim the Plaintiff seeks to assert against the proposed individual defendants are tenable at law.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV: <UNDER>THE LAW</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI>Legal Test for Adding parties under Rules 5.04(2) and 26.01 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM></TI>
<P>17. Rule 26 deals with amendments to a pleading. A properly framed pleading that is tenable at law &ldquo;shall&rdquo; be allowed unless it results in prejudice that cannot be addressed in costs or an adjournment. The onus lies upon the defendant to show non-compensable prejudice under the rules. Rule 26.01 provides:
<QUOTE><P>On motion at any stage of an action the court shall grant leave to amend a pleading on such terms as are just, unless prejudice would result that could not be compensation for by costs or an adjournment.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>18. Rule 5.04(2) deals specifically with the addition of a party. Rule 5.04(2) provides:
<QUOTE><P>At any stage of a proceeding the court may by order add, delete or substitute any party or correct the name of a party incorrectly named, on such terms as are just, unless prejudice would result that could not be compensated for by costs or an adjournment.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>19. Unlike Rule 26.01, the authority to add a party under Rule 5.04(2) is discretionary as the issue of prejudice must be considered before adding a party.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Rooplal v Fodor</SOC><CITE>2018 ONSC 399</CITE><PARANUM>23-24</PARANUM></CASEREF> [<EM>Rooplal</EM>].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Notably, prejudice is automatically assumed where the claim is brought beyond the expiry of the limitation period.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Frohlick Pinkerton Canada Ltd</SOC><CITE>2008 ONCA 3</CITE><PARANUM>17-18</PARANUM></CASEREF> [<EM>Frohlick</EM>]; <CASEREF><SOC>Skrobacky (Litigation guardian of) v Frymer</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 4544</CITE><PARANUM>9</PARANUM></CASEREF> [<EM>Skrobacky</EM>].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> There are no special circumstances available to extend the limitation period under the <EM>Limitations Act, 2002</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Joseph v Paramount Canada's Wonderland</SOC><CITE>2008 ONCA 469</CITE><PARANUM>13, 26-27</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>20. On a motion to add a party under Rule 5.04, the <EM>Limitations Act</EM> imposes a burden on the plaintiff to demonstrate with evidence why the identity of the party and the claim against it could not have been discovered with due diligence prior to the expiry of the limitation period.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Skrobacky</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para 12.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>21. Section 21(1) of the <EM>Limitations Act</EM> prohibits the addition of a party to an existing proceeding if a limitation period in respect of claim against the person has expired.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="V">PART V: SUBMISSIONS</TI>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI>The Plaintiff's claim as against the proposed individual defendants is statute-barred under the <EM>Limitations Act, 2002</EM>.</TI>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>(i)</EM></N><TI><EM>Presumption of Prejudice that cannot be compensated for by costs</EM></TI>
<P>22. The Plaintiff relies on subsection 21(2) of the <EM>Limitations Act</EM> to argue that where the issue is that of correction of a misnaming or misdescription of a party, subsection 21(1) does not prevent the adding of a party to an existing proceeding following the expiry of a limitation period.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Factum of the Plaintiff dated December 11, 2018, at paras 37-38 and</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Plaintiff otherwise concedes that her request to amend the Statement of Claim to add the proposed individual defendants is barred by the operation of the <EM>Limitations Act</EM>.</P>
<P>23. The court's discretionary power under Rule 5.04(2) is limited by subsection 21(1) of the <EM>Limitations Act</EM>. In this case, the Respondent submits that the Plaintiff is not entitled to rely on subsection 21(2) because this is not a case of misnomer or a technical irregularity.</P>
<P>24. The Ontario Court of Appeal has held that where a limitation period has passed, there will be a presumption of prejudice that cannot be compensated for by costs or an adjournment. The burden is on the moving party to demonstrate why the court should not apply the normal rule that presumption of prejudice flowing from the loss of the limitation period is determinative.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Frohlick</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para 22.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Respondent submits that the Plaintiff has not discharged this burden.</P>
<P>25. The attempt to add the proposed individuals as defendants is not merely a procedural step. The limitation period is a substantive and justified barrier to endless exposure to liability through litigation.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>(ii)</EM></N><TI><EM>The jurisprudence relied upon by the Plaintiff is distinguishable</EM></TI>
<P>26. The jurisprudence relied upon by the Plaintiff is distinguishable from the circumstances underpinning the case at bar. The Plaintiff relies on cases where the name of an intended defendant was either omitted by inadvertence or omitted due to error of counsel in the statement of claim. No such evidence has been presented by the Plaintiff in this case.</P>
<P>27. The Affidavit of Ursula Nicola, a legal assistant with the law firm of the Plaintiff's counsel, simply states that the Notice of Action was drafted by former counsel, John D. R. Craig of Fasken. The Affidavit then states that the Plaintiff's current counsel prepared the original Statement of Claim which included the names of the proposed additional five defendants. The Plaintiff presents absolutely no evidence to show that former counsel omitted the names of the proposed individuals unintentionally or by error. The Plaintiff is asking this Court to make an inference that is not available based on the record provided.</P>
<P>28. The Notice of Action in this matter was drafted by experienced counsel, allegedly upon the instruction of the Plaintiff although the Plaintiff is identified as the issuer of the Notice of Action associated with a law firm in Israel. There is no evidence to suggest that the decision to not name the proposed individual defendants was not a deliberate and a tactical decision made as part of the litigation strategy employed by the Plaintiff's former counsel.</P>
<P>29. The Plaintiff is correct to note that a Notice of Action is intended to be brief with the expectation that the details of the claims made will be expanded upon in the Statement of Claim. However, she fails to acknowledge that the Statement of Claim not only expands upon the details of the claims made in the Notice of Action, but it also raises new allegations under the tort of intentional infliction of mental suffering which was not contemplated in the Notice of Action.</P>
<P>30. In <CASEREF><SOC>Hastings v Halton Condo Corp</SOC></CASEREF><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Book of Authorities of the Plaintiff (BOAP), <CASEREF><CITE>2013 ONSC 175</CITE></CASEREF>, Tab 1 [<EM>Hastings</EM>].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>, for example, the plaintiff presented evidence that she specifically instructed her counsel to commence proceedings against various defendants. In preparing the statement of claim, one individual's name was accidentally deleted from the style of cause and the address portion of the statement of claim.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM>, at paras 3 and 4.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Therefore, by inadvertence, that individual's name was not shown as a party defendant in the style of cause.</P>
<P>31. In reaching a decision, the court in <EM>Hastings</EM> relied on the fact that the plaintiff had notified the intended defendant of her intention to make a claim against him by writing him a letter prior to the expiration of the limitation period. In doing so, the plaintiff demonstrated that the intended defendant had knowledge that he was an intended defendant <EM>prior to</EM> the issuance of the statement of claim and <EM>prior to</EM> the expiration of the limitation period.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM>, at para 11 and 13.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>32. In <EM>Corp. of Township of North Shore v Grant</EM><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><CITE>2018 ONSC 503</CITE></CASEREF> [<EM>Township</EM>].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>, the Court held that regardless of how a request to add or substitute a party is characterized (i.e. be it a &ldquo;technical irregularity&rdquo; or &ldquo;misnomer or misdescription&rdquo;), the jurisprudence is clear that an amendment will be permitted where there is a &ldquo;coincidence&rdquo; between a plaintiff's intention to sue and the intended defendant's knowledge of the plaintiff's intention.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM>, at paras 20 and 21.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>33. In the case at bar, the Plaintiff notified the AGC of her intention to amend the Statement of Claim to add the proposed individual defendants <EM>after</EM> the expiry of the limitation period. The Plaintiff has not provided any evidence to show &ldquo;coincidence&rdquo; between her intention to sue and the intended defendants' knowledge of that intention in the manner contemplated in <EM>Township</EM>.</P>
<P>34. In <CASEREF><SOC>Dupuis v W.O. Stinson &amp; Son Ltd</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 4317</CITE></CASEREF><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>BOAP, Tab 3 [<EM>Dupuis</EM>].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>, the irregularity was the counsel's failure to attend at court personally to ensure the statement of claim was issued. The plaintiff's counsel learned that the statement of claim had not been issued days later. The court attributed the irregularity to the error of counsel.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM>, at paras 3-4 and 16.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The technical irregularity described in <EM>Dupuis</EM> is distinguishable from the circumstances of this case where the Plaintiff has not presented a scintilla of evidence to suggest an error committed by her former counsel.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI>The Plaintiff's allegations against the proposed individual defendants are not tenable at law.</TI>
<P>35. Not only has the limitation period to add the aforementioned individuals as defendants to the action expired the Respondent submits that the Plaintiff's request to add the individual defendants ought to not succeed as the allegations disclose no reasonable cause of action.</P>
<P>36. The following elements must be demonstrated to establish a tort of intentional infliction of mental suffering:<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Prinzo v Baycrest Centre for Geriatric Care</SOC><CITE>[2002] OJ No 2712</CITE><COURTJUR>CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at paras 43 and 48.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>
<P1>(i) Flagrant or outrageous conduct;</P1>
<P1>(ii) Calculated to produce harm; and,</P1>
<P1>(iii) Resulting in a visible and provable injury/illness.</P1></P>
<P>37. To establish intentional infliction of mental suffering, the plaintiff must not only show that the defendant ought to have known that harm would occur, but it must be shown that the defendant must have intended to produce the kind of harm that occurred or have known that it was almost certain to occur<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Boucher v Wal-Mart Canada Corp</SOC><CITE>2014 ONCA 419</CITE><PARANUM>44</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>38. The Plaintiff's Statement of Claim alleges that the conduct forming the basis of the tort of intentional infliction of mental suffering occurred while she held her position as Canadian Ambassador to Israel. The period of this appointment was January 2, 2014 to June 30, 2016.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>MRP, Statement of Claim, Tab C, at paras 14, 100 and 104.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>39. The Plaintiff's claims against the proposed individuals is frivolous and discloses no reasonable cause of action. The Plaintiff's complaint against the proposed individuals can be summarized as follows:
<P1>(i) Mark Gwozdecky allegedly made efforts to &ldquo;sideline&rdquo; the Plaintiff in her position as Ambassador;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>MRP, Statement of Claim, Tab C, at paras 23&ndash;29.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>(ii) Mark Gwzodecky allegedly &ldquo;threatened&rdquo; the Plaintiff by sending her an article about a former Canadian diplomat being disciplined for concerns about an Official Residence;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>MRP, Statement of Claim, Tab C, at para 31.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>(iii) Daniel Jean allegedly sought to undermine the Plaintiff, make her appear incompetent and strip her of her authority;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>MRP, Statement of Claim, Tab C, at para 39.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>(iv) Daniel Jean allegedly told the Plaintiff &ldquo;we can do whatever we want to you&rdquo; on March 26, 2016 in reference to her departure from her position as Ambassador;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>MRP, Statement of Claim, Tab C, at paras 79&ndash;81.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>(v) Barbara Richardson conducted an inspection that allegedly targeted the Plaintiff following the summer of 2014;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>MRP, Statement of Claim, Tab C, at paras 43&ndash;45.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>(vi) Barbara Richardson released an inspection report that allegedly comprised of &ldquo;unfounded, defamatory conclusions regarding the Plaintiffs conduct, leadership and competency&rdquo;;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>MRP, Statement of Claim, Tab C, at para 46.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>(vii) Alex Bugailiskis allegedly instructed the Plaintiff to be dishonest to the media by saying that she was not available for interviews;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>MRP, Statement of Claim, Tab C, at paras 70&ndash;72.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>(viii) Alex Bugailiskis allegedly engaged in &ldquo;direct, personal attacks of the Plaintiff&rdquo;;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>MRP, Statement of Claim, Tab C, at para 73.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>(ix) Katie Telford allegedly &ldquo;ignored&rdquo; direct correspondence from the Plaintiff on two occasions, being June 13, 2016 and June 20, 2016; and,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>MRP, Statement of Claim, Tab C, at paras 114 and 115</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>(x) Katie Telford allegedly &ldquo;ignored&rdquo; correspondence from the Plaintiff to the Deputy Minister of Global Affairs on which she was copied.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>MRP, Statement of Claim, Tab C, at paras 113-114.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P>40. The allegations made by the Plaintiff do not rise to the level of &ldquo;flagrant and outrageous&rdquo; conduct. The Plaintiff has failed to plead any material facts to support her allegations of being &ldquo;sidelined&rdquo;, &ldquo;threatened&rdquo;, &ldquo;undermined&rdquo; or suffering &ldquo;personal attacks&rdquo;. The Plaintiff makes bold allegations that are devoid of any particulars. The Plaintiff has also failed to plead any material facts to support her allegations of suffering any injury or illness as a result of the alleged flagrant or outrageous conduct.</P>
<P>41. Under Rule 26.01, the proposed amended pleading must be legally tenable and disclose a cause of action.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Plante v Industrial Alliance Life Insurance Co</SOC><CITE>[2003] OJ No 3034</CITE><PARANUM>21</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Respondent submits that the Plaintiff's allegations against the proposed individual defendants based on the tort of intentional infliction of mental suffering are not legally tenable and disclose no reasonable cause of action when considering the test to be applied to establish the tort.</P>
<P>42. While the Plaintiff alleges that she suffered a visible and provable injury as a result of the proposed individual defendants' flagrant and outrageous conduct that were calculated to harm her, she does not plead any material facts as to what visible and provable injury she has suffered nor does she plead any facts regarding when she suffered these alleged injuries.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="VI">PART VI: ORDER SOUGHT</TI>
<P>43. The Respondent requests that this motion be dismissed, with costs.</P>
<P><BOLD>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED</BOLD></P>
<P>Dated at Toronto this 9th day of January, 2019.</P>
<P>&ellip35; Barney Brucker</P>
